    "The 'interruption cost gradient' rises with task complexity — interrupting a simple task costs 4–5 minutes to recover; interrupting complex creative or analytical work costs 20–25 minutes on average, making the value of uninterrupted blocks rise non-linearly with task difficulty.",
    "The 'Simon effect' — faster response when the stimulus and response are on the same side, even when side is irrelevant — reveals that spatial processing is automatic and cannot be switched off; workspace layout that aligns stimulus and response spatially reduces cognitive load in any task involving spatial decisions.",
    "Intrinsic cognitive load (from task complexity) is irreducible — but extraneous cognitive load (from poor presentation and environment) is entirely under your control; the single most impactful learning environment intervention is eliminating extraneous load rather than trying to 'push harder.'",
    "The 'modality mismatch' effect: requiring learners to process visual and auditory streams that present complementary (not redundant) information maximizes dual-channel cognitive bandwidth use; presenting the same information in both channels simultaneously (redundancy effect) wastes bandwidth and reduces net learning.",
    "Semantic 'self-relevance' encoding (asking 'how does this apply to me?') is the strongest single-item encoding amplifier available — information judged personally relevant is later recalled at 2–3x the rate of equivalently reviewed information judged irrelevant.",
    "The 'error positivity' ERP component measured by EEG reveals that the brain detects its own errors within 80–100ms — before conscious awareness — making immediate course correction neurologically automatic; training yourself to act on this pre-conscious error signal rather than rationalizing it is a direct performance improvement.",
    "Visual search efficiency (finding a target among distractors) is highly trainable and transfers partially to reading speed, scene appraisal, and proofreading accuracy — any activity requiring visual search under time pressure (Where's Waldo, radiology training, inspection tasks) directly trains this foundational perceptual ability.",
    "The 'executive function battery' includes inhibition, updating, and shifting as separable factors — they correlate moderately with each other but respond to different training interventions (inhibition: stop-signal tasks; updating: n-back; shifting: task-switching paradigms), meaning targeted training is more efficient than generic 'brain training'.",
    "The 'dual-process speed-accuracy tradeoff': System 1 is fast but error-prone in novel domains; System 2 is slow but accurate in novel domains — the optimal strategy for any given decision combines recognizing which process has jurisdiction over that domain and deliberately engaging System 2 when System 1 has not yet accumulated sufficient training data.",
    "Sustained attention requires periodic voluntary 'renewal' — briefly defocusing and explicitly re-focusing on the task goal — to prevent the involuntary attentional fatigue that accumulates during unbroken vigilance tasks; this renewal is distinct from distraction because it is self-initiated and goal-directed.",
    "'Inattentional blindness' (missing prominent stimuli while focused on something else) demonstrates that conscious attention is genuinely limited — the brain does not process the full visual field at once but only what is explicitly attended to, explaining why focused operators in high-stakes environments require systematic checklists rather than relying on attention alone.",
    "Pre-task 'if-then planning' (specifying exactly what you will do when an anticipated obstacle arises) reduces the in-the-moment PFC demand of problem-solving by converting uncertain future decisions into pre-committed implementation responses, freeing cognitive resources for the primary task.",
    "The 'cognitive reserve hypothesis' proposes that intellectually enriched lives build a buffer of synaptic density that delays the functional expression of neurodegeneration — decades of cognitively demanding work is literally a longevity insurance policy for brain performance.",
    "The 'functional fixedness' pattern extends beyond physical objects to cognitive strategies — once you've solved a problem type one way, applying a different strategy requires deliberate meta-cognitive effort to recognize that a better strategy exists; periodic 'strategy audits' prevent functional fixedness from calcifying into inefficiency.",
    "The 'mental simulation' advantage of detailed planning comes from the hippocampal 'future simulation' network accurately predicting implementation obstacles — plans created through vivid mental simulation of execution (step by step) reveal far more implementation challenges than abstract high-level planning.",
    "Attentional 'wandering' (mind-wandering) is associated with activity in the default mode network — brief scheduled mind-wandering sessions (5–10 minutes of unstructured thought after each 45-minute work block) integrate DMN activation into the workflow rather than suppressing it, reducing the frequency of unwanted intrusive DMN activation during focus.",
    "The 'levels of abstraction' principle in problem-solving: the level at which you define a problem determines the range of solutions you can consider — moving up one level of abstraction (from 'how do I write this report faster?' to 'how do I produce this information for my stakeholders most effectively?') expands the solution space and frequently reveals higher-leverage alternatives.",
    "The 'cognitive stack' effect in deep work: each new tool, application, or process added to your workflow stack adds not only its own cognitive learning curve but a permanent maintenance overhead — ruthlessly minimizing the cognitive stack (fewer tools, used more deeply) produces compounding focus gains over time.",
    "Strategic 'cognitive offloading' to trusted systems (GTD, Zettelkasten, systematic project notes) directly extends effective working memory capacity — the cognitively richest minds in history (Darwin, Newton, Leibniz) were systematic externalizers of thought, not merely brilliant internal processors.",
    "Perceptual expertise (the ability to rapidly categorize complex stimuli at the expert level) requires approximately 10,000 pattern-recognition exposures for each major sub-domain — radiology, chess, bird watching, wine tasting, and code review all follow this exposure-to-expertise curve, regardless of training method.",
    "The 'negative transfer' risk of skill generalization: skills learned in one context can actively impair performance in slightly different contexts if the differences are not explicitly recognized — deliberate 'contrast training' (practicing both the original and modified context in alternation) prevents negative transfer by highlighting the discriminating features.",
    "Increasing the 'granularity' of your cognitive vocabulary for a domain (learning precise technical terms) is not mere pedantry — named concepts reduce working memory load by compressing entire sets of relationships into single retrievable chunks, which is why domain jargon is cognitively efficient for experts even when socially alienating.",


